Example: based on MISTIE III

Functional Outcome & Mortality in Hemorrhagic Stroke

MISTIE-III Trial: (Hanley et al. 2019)

  • Hemorrhagic Stroke:
    • Intracranial Hemorrhage (ICH) with or without Intraventricular Hemorrhage (IVH)
  • 1:1 randomized - minimally invasive surgery + thrombolytic vs. SOC medical management
  • Safety & Efficacy: Functional outcome on Modified Rankin Scale (MRS)
    • MRS at 30, 180, and 365 days post randomization
    • Mortality: Administratively censored at 1-year follow-up
  • Good Outcome: MRS 0-3 vs. 4-6 - independent vs. not
  • Simulated data based on actual trial data: not actual study data.

Simulated MISTIE Data:

  • Baseline Covariates
    • age: Age in years
    • male: male sex
    • hx_cvd: cardiovascular disease history
    • hx_hyperlipidemia: hyperlipidemia
    • on_anticoagulants: on anticoagulants
    • on_antiplatelets: on antiplatelets
    • ich_location: ICH: (Lobar, Deep)
    • ich_s_volume: ICH volume on stability scan
    • ivh_s_volume: IVH volume on stability scan
    • gcs_category: presenting Glasgow Coma Score

  • Treatment:
    • arm: treatment arm
    • ich_eot_volume: intracerebral hemorrhage volume on end-of-treatment scan
  • Outcome:
    • Modified Rankin: _complete: completely observed
    • mrs_30d: MRS at 30 days (0-3, 4, 5, 6)
    • mrs_180d: MRS at 180 days (0-2, 3, 4, 5, 6)
    • mrs_365d: MRS at 365 days (0-1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6)
    • days_on_study: days until death/censoring
    • died_on_study: participant died (1) or censored (0)

Installing R Packages from GitHub

  • CRAN: Comprehensive R Archival Network
    • Can use install_packages() to install packages from CRAN, BioC, R-Forge
  • RTools: Tools for compiling packages from source
  • Github: developing software and documentation with version control
    • Can Use devtools::install_github to install packages hosted on Github
  • Installed packages can be loaded using library()

Conventional Unadjusted Estimators:

  • Kaplan Meier: assumes censoring independent of event time in treatment arm
    • Violated: baseline covariates associated with event times & dropout (Dı́az et al. 2018)
  • Logrank Test: valid if censoring is independent of treatment or the event time in each treatment arm (Lancker, Dukes, and Vansteelandt 2021).
    • Most powerful under proportional hazards assumption: weighted logrank test (Lin and León 2017)
  • Cox Proportional Hazards (PH) Model: Score test equivalent to Logrank Test
    • Valid test of null: Sandwich estimator is used and either:
      • Censoring conditionally independent of treatment assignment given the covariates
      • Censoring conditionally independent of the covariates given treatment assignment
    • PH Assumption violated: weighted average of hazards, depend on censoring distribution
    • Hazard: time-varying instantaneous rate of events occur:
      • Does not quantify the expected length of time until the event (Rudser, LeBlanc, and Emerson 2012)

Alternatives to Logrank & Cox PH

  • Time Horizon: specific, clinically meaningful time to assess outcome: \(\tau\)
  • Restricted Mean Survival Time: average time-to-event (e.g. life expectancy when mortality is the event of interest) from baseline to a pre-specified point in time, denoted \(\tau\).
  • Survival Probability (SP): probability of being event-free at a pre-specified point in time, denoted \(\tau\).
  • SP and RMST interpretable when PH assumption is violated: Clinically relevant
  • Doubly-robust estimators for SP and RMST and estimators exist - at least as efficient as the K-M estimator (Dı́az et al. 2018).

Kaplan Meier

time_to_death_km <-
  survfit(
    formula =
      Surv(time = days_on_study,
           event = died_on_study) ~ arm,
    data = sim_miii
  )

ggsurvplot(
  fit = time_to_death_km,
  conf.int = TRUE,
  risk.table = TRUE,
  xlab = "Days", 
  ylab = "Survival probability"
)

Logrank Test

  • Logrank test (G-rho family of tests): survival::survdiff

         event = died_on_study) ~ arm,
  data = sim_miii
)

Unadjusted Cox Model:

unadjusted_cox <-
  survival::coxph(
    formula =
      Surv(time = days_on_study,
           event = died_on_study) ~ arm,
    ties = "efron",
    robust = TRUE,
    data = sim_miii
  )
summary(unadjusted_cox)

Proportional Hazards Assumption

unadjusted_cox_ph_test <-
  cox.zph(unadjusted_cox)
print(unadjusted_cox_ph_test)
# Plot Proportionality Results
plot(cox.zph(unadjusted_cox),
     main = "Proportional Hazards Test")
abline(h = 0, col = "red")

Unadjusted Restricted Mean Survival Time

  • RMST in first 90 days:
  • 83 days in the surgical arm
  • 76 days in the medical arm
  • Difference: 7.1 days
  • Ratio: 1.09 (9% increase in RMST).
with(
  sim_miii,
  survRM2::rmst2(
    time = days_on_study,
    status = died_on_study,
    arm = tx,
    tau = 90
  )
)

Hanley, Daniel F, Richard E Thompson, Michael Rosenblum, Gayane Yenokyan, Karen Lane, Nichol McBee, Steven W Mayo, et al. 2019. “Efficacy and Safety of Minimally Invasive Surgery with Thrombolysis in Intracerebral Haemorrhage Evacuation ( MISTIE III): A Randomised, Controlled, Open-Label, Blinded Endpoint Phase 3 Trial.” The Lancet 393 (10175): 1021–32. https://doi.org/10.1016/s0140-6736(19)30195-3.

Lancker, Kelly Van, Oliver Dukes, and Stijn Vansteelandt. 2021. “Principled Selection of Baseline Covariates to Account for Censoring in Randomized Trials with a Survival Endpoint.” Statistics in Medicine 40 (18): 4108–21. https://doi.org/10.1002/sim.9017.

Lin, Ray S., and Larry F. León. 2017. “Estimation of Treatment Effects in Weighted Log-Rank Tests.” Contemporary Clinical Trials Communications 8 (December): 147–55. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.conctc.2017.09.004.

Rudser, Kyle D., Michael L. LeBlanc, and Scott S. Emerson. 2012. “Distribution-Free Inference on Contrasts of Arbitrary Summary Measures of Survival.” Statistics in Medicine 31 (16): 1722–37. https://doi.org/10.1002/sim.4505.
